{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17534558","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17534558"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:48:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:48:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15149"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15149","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15149"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.59,0.11,0.15,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7837"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92189"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7837","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7837"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15149"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75521"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"38"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"3672"},{"type":"tags","id":"11701"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19107"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31456"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92189","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/92189"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old veterinarian presents to the Emergency Department with fever and headache. Three days ago, she examined a horse at a property in rural Queensland. The horse had presented with respiratory distress, facial swelling, and ataxia before dying suddenly. The veterinarian was wearing gloves but no mask during the examination. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 125/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 97% on room air, and temperature 38.5\u00b0C. The remainder of the examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely implicated pathogen?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Nipah virus","Hendra virus","Ross River virus","Murray Valley encephalitis virus","Japanese encephalitis virus"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical scenario strongly suggests \u003Cstrong\u003EHendra virus\u003C/strong\u003E infection. The combination of exposure to a horse in Queensland displaying typical signs (respiratory distress, facial swelling, and neurological symptoms) followed by sudden death is characteristic. The virus has only been identified in Australia, particularly in Queensland and northern New South Wales.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENipah virus\u003C/strong\u003E is a related paramyxovirus that causes similar symptoms and is found in Southeast Asia, particularly Malaysia and Bangladesh, with fruit bats as the natural reservoir. It has never been identified in Australia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERoss River virus\u003C/strong\u003E is a mosquito-borne virus endemic to Australia, but typically causes arthralgia and rash rather than respiratory or neurological symptoms. It does not affect horses in this way and is not transmitted directly from animals to humans.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMurray Valley encephalitis virus\u003C/strong\u003E is a mosquito-borne flavivirus found in Australia that can cause encephalitis, but it does not primarily affect horses and is not transmitted through direct contact with animals.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EJapanese encephalitis virus\u003C/strong\u003E is another mosquito-borne flavivirus that can affect both horses and humans but is not endemic to Australia (though occasional outbreaks occur). The transmission pattern and clinical presentation are different from this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHendra virus infection requires immediate notification to public health authorities and management in appropriate containment facilities due to its high mortality rate and potential for human-to-human transmission. The natural reservoir for Hendra virus is flying foxes (fruit bats), with horses acting as intermediate hosts.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Hendra virus is a paramyxovirus that primarily affects horses but can be transmitted to humans through close contact.","The virus has only been identified in Australia, particularly in Queensland and northern New South Wales."],"references":["Hanna JN, McBride WJ, Brookes DL, et al. Hendra virus infection in a veterinarian. Med J Aust. 2006;185(10):562-564. doi:10.5694/j.1326-5377.2006.tb00692.x"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75521"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15149"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75521","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/75521"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-16T20:22:38+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-16T20:22:39+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7837"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92189"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id"